'''''La Bible amusante pour les grands et les enfants''''' (''The Amusing Bible for Grown-ups and Children'') was a book by [[Léo Taxil]] with illustrations by [[Frid'rick]] published in 1882 by [[Libraire anticléricale]], in which he pointed out what he considered to be inconsistencies, errors and false beliefs.<ref>{{cite book |title=Word crimes: blasphemy, culture, and literature in nineteenth-century England |last=Marsh |first=Joss |year=1998 |publisher=[[University of Chicago Press]] |isbn=978-0-226-50691-3 |page=140 }}</ref> At the time of publication the author was accused of irreverently mocking the Bible.<ref>{{cite news |title=London Town Talk |url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=TS18810516.2.26 |work=The Star |location=[[Christchurch]], New Zealand |date=16 May 1881 |accessdate=4 November 2009 }}</ref> ''[[The Times]]'' called for the book to be suppressed.<ref>{{cite book |title=Vision and realism: a hundred years of the Freethinker |last=Herrick |first=Jim |authorlink=Jim Herrick |year=1982 |publisher=[[G.W. Foote]] |isbn=978-0-9508243-0-7 |page=10 }}</ref>
